D15 0990  7    enjoinder to put aside desires and perturbations so
D15 1000  3    that a return to purity, peace, and stillness- a union
D15 1010  2    with the Infinite, with the Tao- could be effected.
D15 1010 11    In fact, the antipathy to outward ceremonies hailed
D15 1020  7    by modern exponents as so uniquely characteristic of
D15 1030  4    the "direct thinking" Zennist was a feature of Taoism.
D15 1040  3    So, too, was the insistence on the relativity of the
D15 1050  1    external world, and the ideas that language and things
D15 1050 10    perceived by consciousness were poor substitutes indeed
D15 1060  6    for immediate perception by pure, indwelling spirit:
D15 1070  4    the opposition of pure consciousness to ratiocinating
D15 1080  1    consciousness.
D15 1080  2       Zen maintains that cognitive things are only the
D15 1090  4    surface of experience. One of its features attractive
